ing the rules of Parliament." I do not think so—I do not think so. [<em>Interruption</em>] We are playing with the rules? There is only one party that is playing with the rules, and it is called New Zealand First. Why? I will tell you why: because it talks about this vote. It talks about a party vote. </p><p class="a">Actually, pretty much most of us were going to go out and do the community stuff that we are all asked to do, including—oh, maybe not New Zealand First. But, anyway, the rest of us work, and it is common protocol to follow the course of action that is set out. But for one reason—and Taranaki and Manawatū have not been told yet by New Zealand First why—it pulled the plug. </p><p class="a">So, just to help us, I will just take one quote. Here is a quote—this is from Peter Moeahu—"I attended Māori Affairs select committee hearings where submissions were heard, all of them in favour of the bill reading. Their member sat through the select committee process and at that time said there were no problems at all. We can have no idea as to why they called late information, or where this came from. Frankly, we are very disappointed and disgusted at New Zealand First for what they've done." </p><p class="a">My message is this to Te Ao Māori: Te Ao Māori, kia tūpato ki tēnei ngāngara! [<em>Māoridom, be careful with this creepy-crawly!</em>]</p></div></body>
